## <a id='install'></a> Installation

Please follow these [instructions](./installing.html) to install Single Sign-On via Ops Manager.

## <a id='setup'></a> Set Up

### <a id='svc-plan'></a> Create a Service Plan

The Single Sign-On service is a multi-tenant service and a service plan corresponds to a tenant. This allows an enterprise to segregate users or environments using plans.

Follow these [instructions](./manage-service-plans.html) to create a service plan.

### <a id='svc-instance'></a> Create a Service Instance

Single Sign-On service plans can be used across spaces to provide single sign-on capabilities for applications in various spaces. A service instance enables the binding of an application to a service plan.

Follow these [instructions](./manage-service-instances.html) to create a service instance.

### <a id='idp-config'></a> Configure an Identity Provider

In addition to the internal user store, external identity providers can be configured to provide single sign-on to applications. External identity providers must support SAML 2.0.



Follow these [instructions](./manage-id-providers.html) to configure identity providers.

### <a id='reg-apps'></a> Register Applications

Single Sign-On supports both Pivotal Cloud Foundry hosted applications as well as externally hosted applications. Your applications must be able to request an OAuth or OpenID Connect token.

Follow these [instructions](./manage-apps.html) to register your applications.

### <a id='resources'></a> Create Resources

Once your applications are registered you can create resources to permit and restrict user access. These will allow users and clients (or applications) to tell an authorization server what permissions they’ll need on resources they’re accessing.

Follow these [instructions](./manage-resources.html) to create resources for your applications.

## <a id='other'></a> Other Usages

Single Sign-On also supports single sign-on for other components of Pivotal Cloud Foundry. This includes single sign-on to Ops Manager and Apps Manager. This allows the reuse of existing users and credentials that are managed in an external identity provider to sign into Pivotal services.

For more information on how to configure these services to use Single Sign-On, refer to the following pages:

* Ops Manager

* [Apps Manager](http://docs.pivotal.io/pivotalcf/opsguide/sso.html)


